Indian Cricket Team and Blackcaps will be playing their 1st #TestMatch at Kanpur, Uttar Pradesh from September 22, 2016.  

While it has taken 84 years for India to reach this milestone, few would bet on the next 500. Test cricket is in turbulence, and the format that once held a special place in the world of sport, is struggling for survival. Two-tier competition, pink ball and four-day matches are all in the mix, but it appears a losing battle as of now.

Virat Kohli carries the baton in a season packed with 13 home Tests. A strong finish will infuse credibility in Test cricket and dictate the journey ahead.
link_name: India's 500th Test

status_message:
Vatsala Thackeray is 66, arthritic and diabetic, but her work days are only getting longer -- it now begins at 5.30 am and ends at 6.00 pm. Where she used to cook in five homes, she now cooks in seven.

Vatsala earns Rs 17,000 a month, and her son-in-law, a government school teacher, Rs 20,000. Put together, their earnings used to be enough, with some left over for one trip home to their village every year. That stopped two years ago. As prices continued to rise, they stopped all outings within the city too.  

Prices of essential commodities are through the roof. Here, we take a look at how different families are coping: http://read.ht/BGyq
link_name: Watch: People in Delhi discuss how inflation has messed with t...

In a windowless room in Delhi's Gharaunda shelter for the elderly, a group of people watch television, as they wait for lunch. Abandoned by their families in their twilight years, time is all these people have now.

Property disputes lie at the heart of elderly abuse in India. "Once they hand over the ancestral property to their children, the kids tell them to move out of their lives," says Gharaunda's caretaker S Mohanty. Read the HT report on the plight: read.ht/BGeN
link_name: Till property tear them apart
